\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid4144491 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Well, my grandfather was also in the I
ndian Civil Service, in the judicial side, in the judiciary.  So he went out much earlier, it must have been after the end of the Third Burmese War, and he became a judge.  He\rquote 
s an Irishman.  And I think he was quite popular as a wild Irishman.  But as I read the histories like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 The Guardians of India}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
, and other books about the period, I realise that they must have had quite a social strain put on them.  He comes from a happy-go-lucky family in Ireland, and she comes from a very constricted family \endash  my grandmother \endash  as a clergyman
\rquote s daughter.  But he didn\rquote t have a living, he was a Naval Chaplain, and he rather planned to give up, to retire, as there was very little money \endash  he hadn\rquote t got any money of his own at all \endash  and he\rquote 
d planned to open a Dame\rquote s School, but he planned that his eldest daughter \endash  my grandmother \endash  would be the Dame to the Dame\rquote s School, and he would retire on the proceeds of this.  But she didn\rquote 
t fancy that.  But he had had her educated with the boys, so she learnt Latin and Greek and all the
re was, really, to learn, but she learnt it with her brothers, had books thrown at her head like they did - very egalitarian - for not remembering her conjugations of verbs!  And so she was educated, unusually.  But she ran away from home to become a nurs
e.  And that was very daring.  She was a very strong character, but very suppressed and anxious, and I think socially anxious.  I think Philip, who wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 The Guardians}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
, about the Indian Civil Service, and Maurice Collis, say that at the beginning, the Indian Civil Service was recruited from the upper classes in England, and that the level of social hierarchy went right down gradually, very quickly probably.  My father
\rquote s arrival would have been just when it really was turning over to a much more much more ordinary level entrance to the Civil Service.  But the Army had the top social rank, and the Civil Service the next, commerce \endash 
 Anglo-Burmese Oil and things like that \endash  the next, and the Police last, you see.  So if one was conscious of all these ranks and had to entertain and be entertained, it might have been quite a strain for people who weren\rquote 
t used to it.  So they were worried.  She was worried \endash  I don\rquote t think he was.
