Because my grandfather was in Burma, as well as my father, so it was my mother\rquote s mother.  She used to run the Women\rquote s Institute with the other women, and she used to be a judge of apple jam, an
d apple jelly, and she used to keep bees, and she used to have bridge parties to raise money for something or other, and it was always a sort of tremendous anxiety at the local bridge parties.  \'93Oh, I know it\rquote s going to be a fiasco!\'94  \'93
What\rquote s a fiasco, Granny?\'94  (LAUGHS)  You remember these words, you know!  So I knew she was anxious.  Yes.  She was a bit formal with us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Yes.  Yes.  So, really, during that period, you didn\rquote t have somebody who you could talk to about problems.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 We really didn\rquote t 
talk at all, no.  Really didn\rquote t.  No.  We never heard a rude word.  We never had anybody angry or cursing or swearing, or any discussions of money in front of the children.  No!  So we really didn\rquote 
t know what was happening in the world at all!  (LAUGHS)
