\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Good question!  My grandfather, being Irish, my mother was Catholic as well as he, and in those days, she made a promise to bring up the children as Catholics.  And my father didn\rquote 
t mind which way they were brought up.  But he, himself, was a strong agnostic \endash  if you can say that!  He didn\rquote t quite disbelieve in God, but as near as possible, he just kept saying, \'93Well, how does one know?\'94
  And so he had no religion, in effect.  And it was very much part of his 1920s group.  He was a man of the world, it was the 1920s, when I was born, and there\rquote s a nice discussion of which way they went.  I haven\rquote 
t got it in my head now, I can\rquote t remember the kind of social divisions on politics.  But he was definitely not an intellectual political observer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
But you were talking about religion.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
