\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Because I thought one of the grandparents was a Naval Chaplain.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Yes.  My grandmother, who was a stout Protestant, who brought us up, took her duty terribly seriously, and she thought it was her duty to bring us up as Catholics, and so she taught us our Catholic catechism.  And my uncle \endash  her son \endash 
 told us, it was turning the knife in the wound, that she would do it on purpose, because it was her duty.  But it didn\rquote t make much impact on us.  I don\rquote t remember any of that, but I heard about it afterwards.  I don\rquote 
t remember it.  She took us to school, she took us to Sunday School.  And she took us to Mass every Sunday, but then my grandfather went to Mass every Sunday.
