t think Raymond - I don\rquote t know much about that area, it\rquote s not my region at all, but Darryll Forde was a much 
much abler person, I think, in every possible way, and he had done a small amount of fieldwork in West Africa, but he made it his job to really make sure that West Africa was properly ethnographised all round.  So his criticism of Raymond Firth\rquote 
s work was 
that Raymond took seriously that Tikopia was 700 miles away from the nearest civilisation, nearest New Guinea people, 700 miles, and so he felt it was all right to treat their culture as if it had nothing to do with other New Guinea cultures, as if it was
 a thing on its own.  He didn\rquote t really have much contact with the rest of the New Guinea scene, that\rquote s what Darryll thought. \'85 I\rquote 
m out of that area, but remembering what he used to say, I was impressed, because he saw that interaction.
