\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2627783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Yes.  Well, the War came to an end, and the Education Department announced grants for anybody who could prove that their education was incomplete, which was a problem for me, because I\rquote d done my degree.  But som
ehow I managed to get a grant to go back to Oxford, and I particularly wanted to study with Evans-Pritchard. This was a reaction against two people, two anthropologists, Raymond Firth and Bill Stanner, who was a good friend of mine, close friend.  Both of
 them said, \'93You\rquote ll never stay [as an] anthropologist, you\rquote ll have to give up your religion.  There\rquote s no way an anthropologist can be a Catholic\'94
.  Now, the nuns had founded me much too well, intellectually, to know that that could make sense at all.  What 
they were saying was totally superficial, and how much difference can it make to your understanding of your relation with God and institutions that you\rquote 
ve been brought up with, to know that other people have had a different idea of God?  But they thought it did, you see.  And Darryll Forde also.  But that was much later, because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2627783 I was already working for him.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 So I was very careful to go to a place where I wouldn
\rquote t ever be faced with that silly question, and chose to work with Evans-Pritchard, who was known to be a Catholic, by that time.  I tried to go to Cambridge, where he was, and they couldn\rquote 
t find room for me at that point, and so the sort of fall-back position was to go to Oxford, where my old College accepted me, and he\rquote d just started, Evans-Pritchard.  He\rquote 
d left Cambridge to go to Oxford, so I was on the ground floor there.  And then I really started to live!  I wasn\rquote t really at all awake anyway, before that, as you can gather.
