\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
They got him into Cambridge, with great difficulty, because they felt he should have a Chair.  E-P did and Meyer did. And Hutton was retiring in Cambridge, and everybody was trying to get their own candidate in, and so E-P was backing Meyer
 for this, he thought he was by far the most qualified person, and when they went to the meeting, E-P proposed to Hutton, Meyer Fortes, and was met by, \'93Oh no.  No.  We can\rquote t have a Jew here in Cambridge.  No\'94.  So, so he said, \'93
Well, what about Audrey Richards, then?\'94  \'93No, no, we can\rquote t have a woman\'94.  So he said, \'93Well, who would you like?\'94  He said, \'93Well, I think Heyerendorf would be a good person\'94.  He\rquote 
s an Austrian professor in science.  At that time he wasn\rquote t a professor.  So Hutton said, \'93Heyerendorf."  But \'93no Jews, no Catholics\'94 was what Hutton had said.  So E-P thought, \'93He\rquote s a Catholic\'94.  So Hutton said, \'93Oh, he
\rquote s only a native Catholic, that doesn\rquote t count\'94.  But [at Oxford] E-P and the Curator of the Pitt-Rivers Museum were a blocking group together, and they blocked it until Meyer got elected, by their refusing every other candidate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
