\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12649781 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
I soon found I was actually very much in the company of women, and so a lot of the conversation was on food, and what people could eat.  And then I would go back from that conversation about, \'93Women don\rquote t eat this kind of antelope\'94, or \'93
That part of the animal goes to that part of the thing\'94, which I\rquote d read quite a lot about in other people\rquote s anthropology.  Oh, the big instruction we had, which was not about the mechanism of wr
iting notes, but it was about being a scholar of the area.  We were supposed to read everything about that area before we started, and to know all about what had been written before - not on your tribe, your tribe would never have been written about befor
e \endash  mine wasn\rquote 
t, much.  But all about the whole of the lower part of the Congo, I was supposed to know.  So, therefore, I had a basis for comparison for asking questions, you see.  It was very strange, the stuff I had to read.  But I liked that advice, that
 was the kind of advice, you know, it was much more a literary approach.  So when I got to the place where they were all talking about animals, I would say, \'93Why can\rquote t women eat this animal?\'94  Or, \'93Why don\rquote t \'85 why doesn\rquote 
t anybody eat it?\'94 or, \'93Why can only warriors, who have killed a man, eat it?\'94  They\rquote d always start answering me, first of all, \'93Well, that\rquote s what the old people told us\'94, and when I still insisted that wasn\rquote 
t good enough an answer, they said, \'93Well, have you ever seen it?\'94  So I said, \'93No\'94.  And then they would describe it\rquote 
s life habits, the habits and the look of the animal, the appearance of it.  And I realised eventually, not too soon, but within a few months, that they were answering my questions.  And if I put all the answers together a
bout all the animals, I could do something systematic about their view of their universe.  And that then became a very exciting pursuit, so I really sort of focused on animals for a long time.  I had to get the names of the animals translated, because the
re weren\rquote t many left in the forest, they didn\rquote t get them very often.  So I\rquote d get their name, and a Luba man would translate it into Luba, and then there was a game warden in the Luba country \endash  a Belgian \endash 
 who knew what the animal was, from Luba, and then I got it back, so that's how I got it! \tab 
I was the first person to do a systematic account of all the animals that they classified, and a classification of the animals.  But that was what we had been trained to do, you see.  So that would be a system.  It wou
ld be systematic, and it became very easy to systematise it further, you soon found that there were ground animals \endash  under the ground \endash 
 and that these were considered very influenced by the ancestors who were buried under the ground.  And then there were animals on the land, and they were forest animals, or bush animals.  They\rquote 
d be carnivorous or herbivorous, or nocturnal or diurnal, water animals, and by that classification, you found that there was a whole picture of the social system.  There were sky animals \endash  that was squirrels and birds \endash 
 and sky animals had no implications for people, but all the land animals, and the burrowing animals, were so classified that you had a projection of the social system on the menu, who could eat what, you see.  Pregnant
 women this, and women wanting to be pregnant that.  And it was fascinating, it became a marvellous passion for me to watch it and go on asking, and then to get to know the answers myself as I came across new animals.  One that startled me, because I wasn
\rquote t expecting it, all the other animals were in terms of the social structure, but there was a lovely antelope, which they called \'93ibudi\'94, and men couldn\rquote t eat it, which was amazing, because men really didn\rquote 
t leave much to the women.  \'93Why not?\'94  \'93Because it\rquote s so beautiful, only the women can eat it\'94.  Which fits with the impression I was getting of a people who really appreciated female beauty.
