\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15551560 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Oh no.  There were two or three Scholarships I could have applied for, for money for fieldwork.  One was the Beit Scholarship, a South Afri
can one, and I looked up some of the history of the people there, I read them - I particularly remember the Baela - and I found that if I\rquote 
d gone to South Africa, all my fieldwork would have been about political problems, about land tenure, and that wasn\rquote t 
what I was doing anthropology for.  I wanted to know - what I did find, these metaphysics of foreign people, those wonderful romantic ideas they had.  So I didn\rquote t want to apply for that.  And there was another one I didn\rquote 
t apply for, and on social grounds. I wanted to go to a matrilineal people, because there weren\rquote 
t enough descriptions on them, since Audrey Richards.  So fortunately, there was a big conference of the International Commission of Ethnology, and it was being held in Brussels, it was not too f
ar away.  It was a worldwide thing, but it was focused in America, so it was lucky it was that year in Brussels, which is for the Congo, you see.  I was very interested in the Congo at that point.  And if I could get there, I would meet people who could a
dvise me, the Terveulen Museum people, and see about where t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15551560 o go in amongst what is called \lquote the matrilineal belt\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 . (LAUGHS)  And so I sold my mother\rquote s fur coat, which had been treasured all these years, for this purpose, and got \'a320 I think!  And that was q
uite enough to take me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15551560  to Belgium and keep me in the c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 onference for the five days or whatever it was.  So then I met the Curator, Franz Albrechts, and [Georges] Brausch \endash  the District Officer from that part of the Congo \endash 
 and some missionaries and other people.  And Broche said, \'93You must go to the Dali - for one thing, they\rquote re polyandrous, and nobody\rquote s studied polyandry\'94
, and it sounded really attractive!  Another thing, they paint themselves red, so they have bows and arrows, so you can\rquote t be getting further away from civilisation than that!  And the third thing, was that they\rquote 
re matrilineal, yes.  And then they were safe.  Evans-Pritchard just advised us not to go to ridiculously perilous areas where somebody would have to risk their life rescuing you, you
 see.  So that all sounded lined up, and it all went very smoothly.  I was received for a month before I left Europe, by the people in the Museum of Terveulen, who were very good to me, and let me read all this stuff.  I was supposed to be reading about t
he area.
