\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 \'85 all day.  They wouldn\rquote t let me into the forest, in the first village, because they said that the spirits in the forest wouldn\rquote 
t like me going there, and they, themselves, were terribly careful of taboos in a forest, so if I went, a log would fall on me, or I\rquote d fall on a log and I\rquote 
d break a leg, and then the government would be on them like a ton of bricks, and they couldn\rquote t really risk having me around, unless I stayed in the village \endash  which bored me stiff!  I got no exercise, and I couldn\rquote 
t see what was happening.  So the cook said, \'93Come on, we\rquote ll go to my village.  They\rquote ll accept you there, because I\rquote m a son of the village\'94
.  And that was true.  I was able to go into the forest whenever anybody went, and I had a number of women friends who would say, \'93Come on, we\rquote re off.  We\rquote re going to get some water\'94, and so I\rquote 
d go with them.  And that was delightful.  I did lots of thin
gs with them.  But any time I wanted to go and talk to somebody, I could go and sit on - they had these lovely benches that they made out of split bamboo fronds, which they sat on all the time, so I could sit on one.  And they were so polite, you see.  Th
ey\rquote re charming, polite people, so they\rquote d ask me, small talk, you know, and try me out on my language.  \'93Why do we hear that the white people, you have wars, do you?\'94  So I knew they had any amount of warfare, so I said, \'93Yes, we do
\'94.  \'93So what do you fight for those, then?\'94  And this sort of small talk.  So I said, \'93It\rquote s mostly about money\'94.  I said, \'93Oh no, we fight for everything, but perhaps money\'94.  \'93
