\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Yeah.  Yeah.  I think this experience of complete confidence and certainty about everything, and the future, and about what were they to eat on Tuesday, and what you\rquote re going to eat on Wednesday, everything absolutely laid ou
t, was very comforting and good for children who had lost their mother, who were away from their parents.  My mother was alive, but she wasn\rquote 
t with us.  But it completely unfits you for social life in modern England, anyway!  So that when we went to school
, again, it was a hierarchy.  At the first Convent School, and then the second Convent School, the same thing, Mondays and Tuesdays, you knew what you were going to eat, you knew what time to get up, you knew what were the exceptions, and then you had hol
idays which broke all the rules, so there were rules that were made to be broken on the holidays.  What could a holiday be, except by breaking the rules?  And you learnt a lot about formal aspects of co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid290065 -ordination, social relations.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
But when I got to Oxford, none of it worked, and I felt very isolated, lonely, and shy, outside school.  Very confident in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid665544\charrsid6650702 school}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702  and very shy, inarticulate when I left.  It doesn\rquote t fit you for life!  (LAUGHS)  But it did make a tremendous - in a sense, I\rquote 
ve been looking for it ever since - a real hierarchy, in which the top respects the bottom, because they depend on it, this hierarchical structure which you have not just a voice going down, giving the commands, but in which that voice is harkening to wha
t the people are wanting below, because they won\rquote t stand if they don\rquote t say it.  For example, in this article, I think I mentioned \endash  which a biographical article, autobiographical \endash 
 once we heard a nun chastising another nun in front of us once.  We were all shocked.  The abuse of authority, not backing her subordinate, in front of the girls!  We were shocked.  This respect for seniority and juniority \endash  mutual respect 
\endash  was something which I\rquote m looking for always.  You know, the \'93not in front of the servants\'94 business.  We never heard money talked about, we never heard a gross word used, because grandparents don\rquote 
t, and we never heard anything about sex, so we were really completely unfitted for the modern world!
