Yes.  The Lele, yes, the Lele were so attractive to me, for that kind of reason.  They had the kind of egalitarian society, so you can\rquote t call it a normal hierarchy, although there is a move, in contemporary anthropology,
 to find primitive hunters and gatherers as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid665544\charrsid6650702 hierarchs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 , because they\rquote re not egalitarians.  They\rquote re a mixture betwe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid665544 en it.  There
\rquote s a book by Boehm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702  called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Forest Hierarchy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 , and I find it\rquote s very similar to what I saw in the Lele.  People living together and de
pending on each other are very anxious not to upset anybody.  So that the first sort of day amongst the Lele, various people came up to greet me in the village, when I first got installed in the village, in a hut.  They came up to my hut and spoke, and I 
had a very strange looking man, who\rquote d definitely got only one eye, and his face was very deformed.  So when he\rquote d gone, I asked my cook, \'93Who\rquote s that man with one eye?\'94
  How I asked it must have been rather gross, because I really didn\rquote t speak the language well enough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10441448 , but I knew what the word for \lquote eye\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702  was, and I must have pointed to it, and he said, \'93You\rquote ve done something very bad\'94.  I said, \'93What have I done?\'94  He said, \'93
You\rquote ve spoken about it and made a personal remark.  You\rquote ve spoken about somebody\rquote s deformity.  We never do that\'94
.  I felt, then, immediately at home.  I knew what kind of society I was in!  (LAUGHS)  And that went on all the time.  They\rquote re very very sensitive, and very circumspect in all their behaviour.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mmm, that\rquote 
s interesting.  This is very good.  No, going back to the Oxford phase, there were some people that you talked about very well, but other people I think we missed, or didn\rquote 
t really talk enough about.  You did talk about E-P a lot, but Radcliffe-Brown was also around, wasn\rquote t he?  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
E-P succeeded Radcliffe-Brown.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Oh, so you didn\rquote 
t overlap with him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
No, not at all.  But his pupil Franz Steiner had come because of Radcliffe-Brown, and stayed on when he left.  [Radcliffe-Brown] retired then.  And I saw him again}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid11233106 .  He lived in a miserable bachelor\rquote 
s life in a hotel in Tavistock Square, and Darryll Forde was quite nice to him, kept in touch with him.  And he always came to our Christmas Parties, our College Parties.  He gave an occasional lecture, but he was terrib
ly lonely.  An American woman who came over to see him, especially to see this great man, she was shocked that he should be so isolated and so poor.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
