\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Why do you think that happened, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
E-P told me that he couldn\rquote t do anything for Radcliffe-
Brown.  He would like to have.  He never got a proper pension.  He never stayed anywhere long enough to get the equivalent of what they would now call tenure.  So he went to South Africa for a year, he went to Australia for a year, he went to America for 
a year, Canada, I think, and Yale.  But he never stayed anywhere, and I don\rquote t know why.  Didn\rquote t want to.  Yes.  Very strange indeed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 You\rquote 
ve just mentioned Franz Steiner.  Maybe it would be worth saying something more about him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 We\rquote ve been talk
ing about him this morning.  I wrote a preface to the volume that was recently published, of his collected works.  I wrote a preface to the volume called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Taboo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
.  He was tremendously important in our little group.  Did you ever see him?  No, of course not, you\rquote 
re too young!  (LAUGHS)  He was a little chap, very small, about my height, and his eyes were funny, they dazzled, they jumped, it was a disease he had of the eyes.  And, of course, he spoke with a strong German accent.  And he was very sardonic, so it
 was nervous-making conversation.  But he knew Hebrew and Greek, Classics, and he\rquote 
d read all the German philosophers.  I was saying to Marco, I think Marco was asking about what we relation we had to various important German philosophers, and I think it came through Franz Steiner, although I never, myself, read it, or tried to and didn
\rquote t see what to do with it.  And the same with the other ones you mentioned\'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Dilthey.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
I said him, yes.  Meant to, anyway.  Who else you mentioned?  Karl Mannheim 
I never read.  And Steiner European Philosophy, I think, especially German, in our Department.  But he also represented a direct knowledge of the Bible, commentaries of the Bible, and he knew everything.  And he was a poet, and he told me once that he was
 much more famous, in Germany, as a poet, than he was famous as an anthropologist in England.  Well, he wasn\rquote 
t very famous as an anthropologist, because we had a very small group, very small area.  But he lost his thesis.  The tragic thing about him was - 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 He lost it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Mmm.  There were three people I\rquote ve heard of, or more, but he was one of them, whose doctoral thesis was on servitude, as such, and it was a tribute to the history of the Jews, so it was terribly important to him.  We said it was a thesis}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10441448  on slavery, but it was called \lquote servitude\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 .  And if there was anything that we wanted to know about anything, he would be able to give us the most bizarre, extraordinary, far-fetched and d
ifferent models of what we were talking about to open it, and to enable us to be more abstract about what we were doing, not so earthbound and local.  For instance, where the women, in certain kind of marriages, are in the role of servants, and they are s
uffering servitude.  So I was writing my thesis on marriage in Africa, and so that was important for me, the division of labour, of course, and serfdom, and there wasn\rquote t anything that servitude didn\rquote 
t come into.  But his great thesis, that was a really Germanic kind of thesis, which covered }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10441448 everything, what we would call \lquote Teutonic\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
, he left it in a bus, and it was lost completely.  He came to us to try to re-write it.  But he still registered as a doctoral student, this amazing man who knew more than anybody, you know, that one was likely to meet in Oxford really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 And he was important for 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Purity and Danger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 , wasn\rquote 
t he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Yes, because of taboo.  Yes.  Yes, his book on taboo.  Very important.  Opening up all the subjects and giving this general - everything we did depended on him, the more I think about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
