.  We had a little class of our own, three of us.  He said, \'93Well, what\rquote s it about?\'94  So I said, \'93It\rquote s about how you always have to return a gift, and how the person who gets the gift doesn\rquote t forget the person who sent it\'94
.  \'93Is there any more?\'94  \'93No\'94.  That\rquote s what it was about!  (LAUGHS)  I can\rquote t see why it was so important!  (LAUGHS)  I couldn\rquote t see it.  I\rquote 
ve made up for it by writing about gifts quite a lot since then!  (LAUGHS) So Srinivas, also he was a strict vegetarian, and so in the beginning of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Purity and Danger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702  I name him and Steiner as peo
ple who got me on to food taboos.  Yes, mostly in personal relations, his comments in personal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11566113\charrsid6650702 relations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702  are what I remember.  He helped me in my work.  And we all knew his book on the lovely polyandrous people.  What are they called?  Anyway, he \'85 mediate
d Radcliffe-Brown to us.  That was important, because he absolutely doted, admired Radcliffe-Brown tremendously, and talked to him a lot.  And he started with Radcliffe-Brown too.  He stayed on.  He came because of Radcliffe-Brown.  And he had a very form
alist idea of ritual, which was a great help, so that the idea of doing something clockwise and then anti-clockwise \endash  a way of dancing amongst the Courgs (??), the tribes called the Courg \endash 
 but we read that, so we were out to look for ritual relation to society.  That would have been his strong influence on all of us, that we took that for granted after.  He made it very mechanical, I think, yes.
