\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 Mary:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6650702\charrsid6650702 
Well, I found that there was a strong comparative basis, but I didn\rquote t exploit the comparat
iveness in that book, between their food rules and the Bible food rules, the cash (??) of Leviticus.  So what struck me that they had in common, was a big environmental basis for the classification of animals.  I was very interested in the thought that no
 cultural system could ever be complete or determinate, but indeterminacy \endash  that\rquote s the currently fashionable word - but in those days, 1950s, it wasn\rquote 
t at all discussed.  So I knew that the classification system that either of them used couldn\rquote t be determinate for all creation, and that there must be areas which they couldn\rquote 
t include, and how they reacted to those areas.  I then made a jump \endash  I\rquote m going to give you the present day thinking \endash  I made a jump in my mind, then, between the individual facing a classification system, or using one that he\rquote 
s got already from his surroundings, or her surroundings, and the actual making of the classification system itself. \'85
